The stronghold with a 36m-tall round tower was probably built by Hynek Berka of Dube in the second half of the 14th Century. It subsequently owned by Ritka of Bezdedice and the Klinstejns. In the first half of the 16th Century, it was owned by the Berkovsky knights and later by the Kaplirs. 	   However, after it again changed owners, it started to deteriorate since the 17th Century.  There are many legends about robber knights connected with the stronghold. In the 19th Century, it was often depicted by painters as a romantic ruins. The stronghold inspired Karel Hynek Macha to write his work 'Gypsies'. Between 1911 and 1918, it was romantically modified and re-Gothicized by Jan Spacek of Starburg, the last private owner of Kokorin. The building has an elongated ground plan and a 38m-tall tower with a stone helmet. On a staircase leading to the tower, we can find painted emblems of noblemen. In the palace, there are exhibited historical weapons, ceramics and period furniture. There is a sightseeing gallery running along the walls. There are many legends connected to a partially buried well.

I was very surprised not to find anything previously posted on this.

You may remember the huge wildfires that hit southern California a couple of years ago. I created overlays from a couple of maps I found and posted the best one here.

Using these maps, I was able to find the urban fringe areas that were burned and there's a lot damage to be seen. I posted a few placemarks.

Between the maps and Keyhole, there seem to be quite a few areas that are said to be burned but don't look it. Three ways to explain it. 1) Wild Fires jump around and a lot of small areas get skipped over. 2) Ecological resiliency - a lot can happen in 2 years. or 3) The database is old.

Which brings me to a question. How do we have any idea how current an area's database is? For example, am I looking at my house as it is this year, or is it how it looked under the previous owner a couple of years ago? I notice the little copyrights that appear when you're flying over 35,000 feet, and they all seem to say 2005. Are all the images less than a year old? Or are there some parts of the database that are pretty out of date? (Not to be pushy. I'm really just very curious.)

Welcome to Israel!. As you can see, the country is really small (28,000 sqm, about the size of Maryland, or Belgium in Europe),
And yet we are always on the news!!. Why?
This land has a very unique history. Here, 3000 years ago, the Jewish people created a culture which is lasting to this day!.
For 3000 years we speak in the same language, and absorb the same rules of the same religion. Three thousand years!!. No other culture can claim to such a long tradition!.
Moreover, 2000 years ago an off-spring of the Jewish religion, Christianity, emerged here, and changed the history of the western world as never before!.
And although the Jews have been in exile for nearly two thousand years, in 1948 they have re-created the Jewish state called 'ISRAEL'!! After so many years, still this culture managed to recover, return to the land of their fathers, and create its own state!!.
This is an interesting story!. So no wonder the media follows us more then other countries..
So if you are thinking of visiting this country, I invite you to join me for a virtual tour to sites I recommend in Israel.
Enjoy the ride!.

Every region has its claim to fame, but there's none sweeter than Vologda's position as Russia's butter capital. Butter-making, being one of the clearly expressed specializations of the Vologda Oblast, has a many-centuries old tradition. Just mention butter and quality together and every Russian will invariably reply 'Vologda butter'. Vologda butter (Vologodskoe) is a traditional Russian product, with delicious taste and natural lightness. Industrial production of butter on the territory of the Vologda gubernia developed rapidly. In 1913 there were 1290 creameries in the region in comparison to 15 in 1875. At that time the Vologda province produced 20% of butter manufactured in the European part of Russia. Butter became a special item of the Vologda export late in the 19th century. Over the last 100 years the settlement of Molochnoye has evidently become a major centre for dairy farming in the Vologda Oblast. It boasts the Vologda Dairy Academy, a local creamery, a research institute and a livestock breeding farm. There prominent dairy experts take important and innovative initiatives and work hard to create the institutional framework of the Vologda butter production and trade. This delicate and delicious brand is made at only six dairies in the Vologda region.

What started out as a little pet project to find the airports that I had flown to, ended up being a massive undertaking of international proportions. Here is a KMZ file with placemarks for every major international airport and most every other important regional or domestic airport that I could find. Each placemark includes the IATA airport code.

I did my best to let every geographic region be represented, which means that some smaller airports ended up being included. I tried to avoid airports with no regular commercial flights as much as possible, though I am sure some were included especially in the less developed countries.

Information was garnered from a wide variety of sources, including the foreign airports feature on Google Earth, as well as Google searches for various airports and a plethora of sites for individual airports and airports in specific regions.

The key sites that I used to gather the great majority of my information were:

Wikipedia - Airport Category
World Airport Codes
A-Z World Airports

Other sites that were important in providing information and locations were:

Airliners.net
Free Travel Tips Foreign Airport Links
Airlines of the Web Airport Codes
Airports Council International

A couple of interesting notes:

* The 30 busiest airports in the world according to the Airports Council International are ranked with their 2004 passenger total. They are spread out in their geographic regions. I found it interesting to note that Atlanta was number one. I had no idea.

* There is one airport that starts in Canada and ends up in the United States. It is the Piney Pinecreek Border Airport. Look in the folder for Canada.

I hope you enjoy.

Pierre Auger Observatory Surface Detector Station Mimi

This is one of some 1600 particle detectors scattered over a 3000km2 area for the Southern array of the Pierre Auger Observatory, in Mendoza province, Argentina. Another such array is planned for deployment in the Northern hemisphere, in Colorado, USA. With these detectors, the highest energy particles in the Universe are studied: when they strike the Earth's atmosphere, they create a cascade of billions of particles, which can be detected at the ground using water Cherenkov stations (tanks filled with water and equipped with sensitive light detectors). These particles are extremely rare, hence the need to deploy detectors over an enormous area to detect sufficient numbers of them. For more information on the Auger experiment, the water Cherenkov counters, and to see photographs of the actual detectors, see the official Pierre Auger collaboration web site.

The explosion which destroyed the battleship USS MAINE in the harbor of Havana, Cuba on the night of February 15, 1898 was a blast which would continue to echo around the Americas for many years to come. In response to the destruction of the ship, Washington sent American troops and warships to intervene in the Cuban revolt against Spanish colonial rule, and to attack other parts of the Spanish colonial empire, including the Philippines. This attack on Spanish possessions was the first American war against a foreign power since the Mexican-American War of 1845-48. It marked a major change in American foreign policy away from isolationsim and toward a more active role in international affairs, a trend which has continued through the twentieth century. The American victory over Spain, a great power since the time of Columbus which had once dominated much of the world, marked the entrance of the United States into the arena of world powers. As a result, Washington assumed a greater role in the Americas, well beyond the immediate borders of the United States. Americans now had interests in the entire Western Hemisphere, and were no longer occupied with the westward expansion across North America.

What started out as a little pet project to find the airports that I had flown to, ended up being a massive undertaking of international proportions. Here is a KMZ file with placemarks for every major international airport and most every other important regional or domestic airport that I could find. Each placemark includes the IATA airport code.

I did my best to let every geographic region be represented, which means that some smaller airports ended up being included. I tried to avoid airports with no regular commercial flights as much as possible, though I am sure some were included especially in the less developed countries.

Information was garnered from a wide variety of sources, including the foreign airports feature on Google Earth, as well as Google searches for various airports and a plethora of sites for individual airports and airports in specific regions.

The key sites that I used to gather the great majority of my information were:

Wikipedia - Airport Category
World Airport Codes
A-Z World Airports

Other sites that were important in providing information and locations were:

Airliners.net
Free Travel Tips Foreign Airport Links
Airlines of the Web Airport Codes
Airports Council International

A couple of interesting notes:

* The 30 busiest airports in the world according to the Airports Council International are ranked with their 2004 passenger total. They are spread out in their geographic regions. I found it interesting to note that Atlanta was number one. I had no idea.

* There is one airport that starts in Canada and ends up in the United States. It is the Piney Pinecreek Border Airport. Look in the folder for Canada.

I hope you enjoy.

One (small) complaint about Google Earth is that there are very seldom any name tags on islands anywhere.

Columbus, Ohio
Birth place of THACKER, BRIAN MILES
Born 25 April 1945

Rank and organization:-
First Lieutenant, U.S. Army, Battery A, 1st Battalion, 92d Artillery
Date / Location : Kontum Province, Republic of Vietnam, 31 March 1971

Citation :-

 For conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity in action at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty. 1st Lt. Thacker, Field Artillery, Battery A, distinguished himself while serving as the team leader of an Integrated Observation System collocated with elements of 2 Army of the Republic of Vietnam units at Fire Base 6. A numerically superior North Vietnamese Army force launched a well-planned, dawn attack on the small, isolated, hilltop fire base. Employing rockets, grenades, flame-throwers, and automatic weapons, the enemy forces penetrated the perimeter defenses and engaged the defenders in hand-to-hand combat. Throughout the morning and early afternoon, 1st Lt. Thacker rallied and encouraged the U.S. and Republic of Vietnam soldiers in heroic efforts to repulse the enemy. He occupied a dangerously exposed observation position for a period of 4 hours while directing friendly air strikes and artillery fire against the assaulting enemy forces. His personal bravery and inspired leadership enabled the outnumbered friendly forces to inflict a maximum of casualties on the attacking enemy forces and prevented the base from being overrun. By late afternoon, the situation had become untenable. 1st Lt. Thacker organized and directed the withdrawal of the remaining friendly forces. With complete disregard for his personal safety, he remained inside the perimeter alone to provide covering fire with his M-16 rifle until all other friendly forces had escaped from the besieged fire base. Then, in an act of supreme courage, he called for friendly artillery fire on his own position to allow his comrades more time to withdraw safely from the area and, at the same time, inflict even greater casualties on the enemy forces. Although wounded and unable to escape from the area himself, he successfully eluded the enemy forces for 8 days until friendly forces regained control of the fire base. The extraordinary courage and selflessness displayed by 1st Lt. Thacker were an inspiration to his comrades and are in the highest traditions of the military service.

The San Gabriel Mountains of Southern California are steep and rugged, typical of young mountain ranges. Access to their high country is provided by a few sinuous roads. Motorcyclists like them for their curves, as do producers of auto ads. I like them for the great views they provide. If you like mountain roads, these roads are for you. The attachment will download all four tours at once. The following links will download one road at a time, along with the original post I did for each one. (The first one I did was a response to another post (SVT, where did you go?). The others I added on later. I'm dusting them off and presenting them for your touring pleasure under their own heading to make them more accessible.

Angeles Crest Highway

Angeles Forest Highway

Upper Big Tujunga Canyon Road

Big Tujunga Canyon Road

If you are new to the tour option:

1. In the GE viewing window - select edit - select preferences (your only option) - set elevation exaggeration to 1.
2.Make sure 3-D is 'on' and you may want to turn roads 'off'.
3.After you download the attachments, click the '+' sign and open the folder. You will almost certainly see the placemarks out of numerical order. Drag them back into correct order.
4. Click the tour checkbox to checkmark all points and make sure all other checkboxes in My Keyhole are unchecked.
5.Under 'Tour' 'Prefs' in your tool window, set 'pause' time to zero and 'tour speed' to about as slow as it will go.
6. Click 'Play' and you're off. Enjoy.

Also has several bastards from a seriesMay 18-Bren's Plans Didn't Include Legal Spotlight, LA Times  Woman's child-support suit puts the reclusive head of Irvine Co. in an unwelcome spot.   Better views at http://local.live.com/default.aspx?v=2&cp=33.610973~-117.902923&style=o&lvl=1&scene=2346173&sp=adr.Balboa%20Island%20Ferry%2c%20Newport%20Beach%2c%20CA~adr.Blacksheep%2c%20Cordova%2c%20AK%2099574~adr.Linda%20Isle%2c%20Newport%20Beach%2c%20CA%2092660   By Jean O. Pasco, Times Staff Writer   A lawsuit filed last week by a former girlfriend seeking more money for two  children of Irvine Co. real estate mogul Donald Bren has thrust the reclusive  billionaire smack into the public glare he's avoided for decades.   Known as Orange County's Donald Trump for his vast real estate holdings,  Bren's public persona is closer to that of Bill Gates. He makes few  appearances and guards his privacy, while cultivating his image as a  responsible builder of meticulously planned communities.   At 71, the sole owner of  Irvine Co. has an  estimated worth of $4  billion according to  Forbes magazine, which  ranked him 39th among  the richest Americans and  the 78th-wealthiest  person in the world.   Before last week, the  children Bren had  publicly acknowledged were two sons by his first  wife, and a daughter by his second wife — all now  adults — plus a second daughter, now 11, by a  New York artist. But talk of other Bren progeny  has swirled for years.   Because of his penchant for privacy, his closest friends and associates will not talk about this on the  record.   With the lawsuit, 'His bubble's burst now,' said one. 'People like us knew about all this. But now the  public knows about it. He's cultivated his image but it's all been shattered.'   The lawsuit, filed by Jennifer McKay Gold, alleges that Bren has acknowledged paternity and made  support payments to their children, a daughter, 15, and a son, 11. In the last two years, however, Bren  exhibited increasing coldness toward the children, the suit said, and he refused to sign an additional  financial agreement.   Alleging civil fraud and breach of contract, the suit asks for payments for the children commensurate  with Bren's fortune and lifestyle. It also seeks damages for emotional distress and mental anguish. While  the suit does not explicitly seek a place for the children in Bren's will, it does allege that the billionaire  promised 'that he would make provision for their economic welfare.'   http://www.awgpac.com/bbs/messages/1/427.html?1053263863  of mistresses.  http://www.latimes.com/news/local/orange/la-me-bren8jan08,1,6023718.story?coll=la-editions-orange

I created this set because I found this country lacks a lot. Not only placemarks. Particular points of interest are the capital city of P'yongyang and the border to South Korea. Besides this the country is plastered with anti-aircraft sites. Sometimes it is quiet evident what they protect and sometimes they look unfinished or abandoned/dismantled. And I am sure I did not find all and have mistakingly identified a site where it might be something else.

At P'yongyang you can see yourself that this propably the best protected city in the world, at least against air raids. Besides the many many anti-aircraft sites I placed a lot of site-seeing placemarks in P'yongyang. You may find that some interesting looking places have been left out. This is the case because either the place looks interesting but is of minor importance (restuarants and most indoor stadiums just for example) or I could not identify it (The shiny silver dome in down-town P'yongyang for example). I gave my very best to identify the important spots but I did not succed on everything. I took my reference data (maps, commented photographs) from a lot of sites on the internet and cross-verified many of them. If you think you provided some of this information yourself, let me thank you.

At the border I placed some current and historical placemarks. Searching the web for these in combination with the Korean War will for sure bring up some quiet interesting links into the history of this area.

Finaly there's folder 'Other stuff' which contains more or less interesting observations. Mixed bag of military, fun and strange stuff all over the place.

It took me many many hours to complete this collection so don't complain too much .

Enjoy

Additions, corrections and/or comments to wonders at mikane.org are welcome

Icons in red are anti-aircraft sites and have their labels turned off (opacity 0%), icons in green are site-seeing, icons in blue are border placemarks and finaly those in yellow are other stuff.

Update 02/08/06: This place mark set has been refered to in an article by Sonni Efron for LA Times. Sonni asked for an interview but I did not catch his message in time. You might find this interesting. Read his article here: LA Times article 'Google-Earthing the Hermit Kingdom'

column4: Auger Observatory on the Argentine Pampas
column5:
SD Station

Pierre Auger Observatory Surface Detector Station

This is one of some 1600 particle detectors scattered over a 3000km2 area for the Southern array of the Pierre Auger Observatory, in Mendoza province, Argentina. Another such array is planned for deployment in the Northern hemisphere, in Colorado, USA. With these detectors, the highest energy particles in the Universe are studied: when they strike the Earth's atmosphere, they create a cascade of billions of particles, which can be detected at the ground using water Cherenkov stations (tanks filled with water and equipped with sensitive light detectors). These particles are extremely rare, hence the need to deploy detectors over an enormous area to detect sufficient numbers of them. For more information on the Auger experiment, the water Cherenkov counters, and to see photographs of the actual detectors, see the official Pierre Auger collaboration web site.

Al cinema, nelle librerie, nei teatri e in TV i bambini e il loro mondo stanno avendo sempre più attenzione, un fenomeno in continua e rapidissima espansione. A questo fenomeno è dedicato il Mondadori Junior Festival, inaugurato ieri a Verona (Placemark di Google Earth) dove continuerà fino al 1° maggio secondo un programma ricchissimo di appuntamenti. Il tema del Festival di quest’anno è “Tutti i colori del mondo” a testimonianza della volontà di mescolare in modo accattivante e divertente letteratura, arte, teatro, cinema d’animazione, sport, televisione, musica, gastronomia. Le strade, le piazze e i palazzi di Verona ospiteranno cinque giorni di letture, incontri con gli autori, spettacoli, concerti, giochi e animazioni. Sarà una sorta di lunghissimo party, dedicato ai bambini e non solo, capace di coinvolgere il grande pubblico. Nel programma sono inserite oltre ottanta attività con un’incredibile varietà di proposte suddivise in otto sezioni indicate, come suggerisce il titolo del festival, con altrettanti colori. Nel verde, incantesimi di palcoscenico, ci sono gli spettacoli e i concerti; l’arancione, lo faccio anch’io, è il filone dedicato all’interattività attraverso laboratori di pittura e fumetto, di regia, fotografia, stampa e giornalismo; l’azzurro, per i grandi, è uno spazio di incontri e riflessioni dedicato agli adulti, e in particolare a quelli impegnati nell’insegnamento; viola, tutti al cinema, celebra il fascino del grande schermo con la ricostruzione del set di un film; all’attività fisica è invece dedicato il blu, per sport, con la junior marathon e altri appuntamenti “ginnici” per i più piccoli; il giallo, giocando s’impara, propone degli interessanti percorsi per avvicinare i bambini alle scienze attraverso il gioco; il rosso, conoscere il mondo, infine, è il filone dedicato alla multiculturalità e ad importanti temi sociali come l’analfabetismo e il lavoro minorile. Insomma, ci sono appuntamenti per TUTTI i gusti e TUTTI gli interessi: un'occasione da non perdere. Trovate ulteriori informazioni utili qui. post in www.viaggioadagio.it

This ancient sweet chestnut (Castanea sativa) stands in a private garden near the Borders town of Melrose. It is known as the Covin Tree or Trysting Tree, where in days past the family of the house used to greet friends and, in some cases, hang their enemies! The huge, gnarled trunk is of considerable girth, measuring 252cm in diameter (26ft girth) at the standard 1.5m above ground. The original tree is largely dead, but vigorous and well established shoots arising from around the base keep the tree very much alive. A fine, old, named veteran tree with an interesting historical association.

A Great Mtn. Biking loop about an hour from Portland OR

Expect three hours of solid riding to make the 8mile loop. BRING A COMPASS or expect to spend the night and maybe make the news.

Epic uphill challenges and some amazingly technical downhill.

Skip first part of trail and enter Tillamook Historic Hiking Trail at midpoint of Nels Ellis Trail from the logging road. Historic Hiking Trail switches names from Nels Ellis to Wagon Trail after crossing the first river. Make sure to bear left after the river so you don't end up back on the logging roads.

The Historic Trail is the only singletrack hiker/biker only trail along the route, so at any intersection, always go to the nearest singletrack to continue. There is very little motorized accessible track here (at least before University Falls) so always select the singletrack when given a choice.

I created this set because I found this country lacks a lot. Not only placemarks. Particular points of interest are the capital city of P'yongyang and the border to South Korea. Besides this the country is plastered with anti-aircraft sites. Sometimes it is quiet evident what they protect and sometimes they look unfinished or abandoned/dismantled. And I am sure I did not find all and have mistakingly identified a site where it might be something else.

At P'yongyang you can see yourself that this propably the best protected city in the world, at least against air raids. Besides the many many anti-aircraft sites I placed a lot of site-seeing placemarks in P'yongyang. You may find that some interesting looking places have been left out. This is the case because either the place looks interesting but is of minor importance (restuarants and most indoor stadiums just for example) or I could not identify it (The shiny silver dome in down-town P'yongyang for example). I gave my very best to identify the important spots but I did not succed on everything. I took my reference data (maps, commented photographs) from a lot of sites on the internet and cross-verified many of them. If you think you provided some of this information yourself, let me thank you.

At the border I placed some current and historical placemarks. Searching the web for these in combination with the Korean War will for sure bring up some quiet interesting links into the history of this area.

Finaly there's folder 'Other stuff' which contains more or less interesting observations. Mixed bag of military, fun and strange stuff all over the place.

It took me many many hours to complete this collection so don't complain too much .

Enjoy

Additions, corrections and/or comments to wonders at mikane.org are welcome

Icons in red are anti-aircraft sites and have their labels turned off (opacity 0%), icons in green are site-seeing, icons in blue are border placemarks and finaly those in yellow are other stuff.

Nerudova 47, Praha 1 118 00 Prague, Czech Republic  Birthplace of the famous Czech poet, author and journalist, Jan Neruda (Pablo Neruda borrowed Jan's surname). Also known at the House of Twin Suns, due to the 16th-century door sign, carved as Twin Suns on a field of blue. The yellow house is across a small square from a staircase and ramp leading to the front gate of Prague Castle. This building now houses several flats (home to yours truly), a lovely little courtyard, a passable resteraunt and pub and a newsstand. It's a couple of doors down (literally--Nerudova is a big hill) from the only authentic Turkish coffee house in Prague.   Neruda spent the first 22 or so years of his life at this address and then moved across the street to what is now a posh hotel.   And yes, the street, Nerudova, is named after the famous former occupant.

High Desert Church is a group of evangelical Christian communities ministering to approximately 8,000 active participants. HDC is a multi-generational church reaching out to three different generational cultures through separate worship styles and strategic opportunities for personal growth. The core purpose of each of these communities is to prepare people to change their worlds for Christ.  Throughout biblical history, God has utilized the 'extended family' as the primary instrument through which the good news of his love is communicated to the world. The New Testament writers called that group an oikos, (the Greek term for 'household') and everyone has one. On the average, yours is made up of anywhere from eight to fifteen people whom God has supernaturally and strategically placed in your direct sphere of influence. HDC’s ministry is designed to prepare individuals to engage their 'eight to fifteen,' their oikos, with the tremendous news of God’s grace.

In mid-1962, a specially-designated detachment of communications technicians, from the Naval Communications Station, Adak, augmented an operation within a small hut on this site. This activity became known as 'SPECOPS.' It was moved to Zeto Point where it was renamed 'SISS ZULU.' After moving to an improved site on the east side of Clam Lagoon, the operation was known as 'Classic Wizard.' The last facility complex to house this operation is located due north of this marker at North Lake. From its initial inception, this operations served to provide extremely valuable support service to the Navy's tactical fleet units in the Norther Pacific Ocean region, as well as national intelligence authorities.

Columbus, OH: Clear Creek Metro Park. This 5.4 mile ridge hike is a loop that climbs 350 feet to a long ridge and then descends for a walk along the creek back to the car. Many deer, a meadow with thousands of butterflies and a creekside meadow full of wild flowers are highlights. Columbus' 2nd largest and least used Metro Park has many other hike possibilities. We hiked all day Sunday and saw noone else on the trail. TO TRAILHEAD: From I-270, take U.S. 33 SE toward Lancaster. Go about 31 miles to Clear Creek Road (County Route 116 - Sunoco gas station on the corner. 6.9 mi S of Stump-Hollow Rd). Turn right (W) and go about 1.9 miles to the intersection of Clear Creek Road and Starner Road. Park in Creekside Meadows Picnic Area. Hike East on Creekside Meadows Trail to the Cemetary Ridge Trail Head.

com muita alegria que apresento este minucioso trabalho sobre a cidade do Recife, capital do estado de Pernambuco. So mais de 2600 lugares marcados, organizados por temas e categorias, muitos deles com informaes detalhadas referentes aos mesmos. Grande parte destas informaes foi colhida na internet, em sites como Pernambuco.com, JC Online e o da Prefeitura da Cidade do Recife, entre outros. Boa parte delas, contudo, foi parcial ou totalmente reescrita ou adaptada. Tambm serviram de fonte, mapas e folders informativos de turismo, listas telefnicas, enciclopdias e o livro Trilhas do Recife, de Joo Braga, alm de informaes espalhadas por diversos locais da cidade e conversas com transeuntes.
Quando me dei conta que o Recife passou a fazer parte das cidades com imagens detalhadas no Google Earth em 8 de junho de 2006 , comecei esta to esperada empreitada. Amante que sou da Veneza Brasileira, aguardava com muita ansiedade a hora de ver minha cidade 'mais de perto', nesse programa espetacular, para poder iniciar este projeto por amor ao Recife e compartilh-lo com todos os usurios da internet.
Como jamais poderia deixar de faz-lo, agradeo a Deus e a todas as pessoas que me ajudaram na produo deste trabalho, especialmente a meu amigo Roberto Souza (que conhece o Recife bem melhor do que eu, e com muita pacincia neste passeio virtual me apresentou lugares que eu jamais imaginava existir); minha me, Marcia Menezes (pela localizao e catalogao das igrejas da cidade); meu irmo Renato Menezes (por informaes diversas); minha prima Kilma Lima (por valiosas informaes sobre o bairro de Boa Viagem), meus amigos Pedro Augusto (pelas vrias informaes sobre os bairros de Afogados, Mustardinha, Areias e morros do Recife) e Jadson Bispo The Flash (pelas timas informaes sobre vrios pontos da periferia); a Paulo, Clarice e Marcelo Duque (pelo acolhimento em Boa Viagem durante minhas caminhadas pelo bairro); e aos meus colegas do curso de Turismo da Faculdade Maurcio de Nassau, Ricardo Lacerda (pela localizao dos pontos em Olinda) e, ainda mais especialmente, a Rhassa Harrop (que durante todas essas madrugadas insones me ajudou on line com informaes diversas sobre Boa Viagem e na reviso do trabalho a cada atualizao que eu ia fazendo). Tambm professora Onilda Bezerra (por me mostrar que a Ilha do Bananal no o Parque das Capivaras), e professora Daniele Wanderley, por acreditar em mim, pelo encorajamento, inspirao e pela reviso e palavra abalizada que eu sei que viro e devero estar presentes muito em breve. Agradeo ainda a meu pai - Leonardo Sullivan -, a meu irmo Marcio Menezes e a outras pessoas especiais na minha vida, que, embora no tenham contribudo diretamente, foram e sero sempre fonte de inspirao para mim: meus amigos. Jamais teria conseguido ir to a fundo nesta pesquisa sem a amizade e o carinho dessas pessoas. Muito obrigado a todos vocs!
Enfim, este trabalho dedicado a todo o povo brasileiro, principalmente aos pernambucanos. Mais especialmente queles naturais da querida cidade do Recife, e mais especialmente ainda queles que amam esse lugar de corao e no sujam suas ruas, praas e rios.
Certamente que h erros nesta compilao. Assim, agradeo previamente a todos os que puderem apont-los, bem como localizar outros locais interessantes ainda no registrados aqui, para que a gente possa melhor-la nas prximas edies. Espero ainda poder corrigir, atualizar e adicionar mais lugares, sempre que possvel. Conto com a colaborao de todos.
Angelo 'Naninho' Menezes

38km north of 'Koralle' there was a powerful transmitter station named 'Sendestelle Bölkendorf'. This facility supported HQ 'Koralle' and was enlarged in 1944 significantly. Finally there were several surface and underground facilities. For example there was a big telescopic Antenna Mast which could be lowered and extendend right out of the ground and with that getting tuned on the appropriate frequency.

After the war the facilities were destroyed in 1947 but the remains were still seen in the 90ties until the german army cleared up the area completely.
A wonderful green highland!

This is a bunch of placemarks in Bieszczady Mountains, Poland. It contains localizations of numerous peaks, passes, villages and other. This may be particularly useful for people liking to tramp in Bieszczady or wishing to get to know more about Bieszczady's topography.


Bieszczady is a part of Carpathian Mountains, located in south-eastern tip of Poland, aligning to the border with Ukraine. These are still least-populated and developed mountains in Poland. Apart from a lot of wild nature, views, tramping opportunities, etc, it offers an insight into some of its rich history – one who is careful enough to look may find clearings in the forest left after villages abandoned (and many times destroyed) shortly after the WWII, old cemeteries (both Catholic and Jewish), and still some old wooden orthodox churches.

Significant part of Bieszczady is covered by Bieszczady National Park, which is part of the International Biosphere Reserve.

Alas there are no good sites about Bieszczady in English. You can see those:

com muita alegria que apresento este minucioso trabalho sobre a cidade do Recife, capital do estado de Pernambuco. So mais de 2600 lugares marcados, organizados por temas e categorias, muitos deles com informaes detalhadas referentes aos mesmos. Grande parte destas informaes foi colhida na internet, em sites como Pernambuco.com, JC Online e o da Prefeitura da Cidade do Recife, entre outros. Boa parte delas, contudo, foi parcial ou totalmente reescrita ou adaptada. Tambm serviram de fonte, mapas e folders informativos de turismo, listas telefnicas, enciclopdias e o livro Trilhas do Recife, de Joo Braga, alm de informaes espalhadas por diversos locais da cidade e conversas com transeuntes.
Quando me dei conta que o Recife passou a fazer parte das cidades com imagens detalhadas no Google Earth em 8 de junho de 2006 , comecei esta to esperada empreitada. Amante que sou da Veneza Brasileira, aguardava com muita ansiedade a hora de ver minha cidade 'mais de perto', nesse programa espetacular, para poder iniciar este projeto por amor ao Recife e compartilh-lo com todos os usurios da internet.
Como jamais poderia deixar de faz-lo, agradeo a Deus e a todas as pessoas que me ajudaram na produo deste trabalho, especialmente a meu amigo Roberto Souza (que conhece o Recife bem melhor do que eu, e com muita pacincia neste passeio virtual me apresentou lugares que eu jamais imaginava existir); minha me, Marcia Menezes (pela localizao e catalogao das igrejas da cidade); meu irmo Renato Menezes (por informaes diversas); minha prima Kilma Lima (por valiosas informaes sobre o bairro de Boa Viagem), meus amigos Pedro Augusto (pelas vrias informaes sobre os bairros de Afogados, Mustardinha, Areias e morros do Recife) e Jadson Bispo The Flash (pelas timas informaes sobre vrios pontos da periferia); a Paulo, Clarice e Marcelo Duque (pelo acolhimento em Boa Viagem durante minhas caminhadas pelo bairro); e aos meus colegas do curso de Turismo da Faculdade Maurcio de Nassau, Ricardo Lacerda (pela localizao dos pontos em Olinda) e, ainda mais especialmente, a Rhassa Harrop (que durante todas essas madrugadas insones me ajudou on line com informaes diversas sobre Boa Viagem e na reviso do trabalho a cada atualizao que eu ia fazendo). Tambm professora Onilda Bezerra (por me mostrar que a Ilha do Bananal no o Parque das Capivaras), e professora Daniele Wanderley, por acreditar em mim, pelo encorajamento, inspirao e pela reviso e palavra abalizada que eu sei que viro e devero estar presentes muito em breve. Agradeo ainda a meu pai - Leonardo Sullivan -, a meu irmo Marcio Menezes e a outras pessoas especiais na minha vida, que, embora no tenham contribudo diretamente, foram e sero sempre fonte de inspirao para mim: meus amigos. Jamais teria conseguido ir to a fundo nesta pesquisa sem a amizade e o carinho dessas pessoas. Muito obrigado a todos vocs!
Enfim, este trabalho dedicado a todo o povo brasileiro, principalmente aos pernambucanos. Mais especialmente queles naturais da querida cidade do Recife, e mais especialmente ainda queles que amam esse lugar de corao e no sujam suas ruas, praas e rios.
Certamente que h erros nesta compilao. Assim, agradeo previamente a todos os que puderem apont-los, bem como localizar outros locais interessantes ainda no registrados aqui, para que a gente possa melhor-la nas prximas edies. Espero ainda poder corrigir, atualizar e adicionar mais lugares, sempre que possvel. Conto com a colaborao de todos.
Angelo 'Naninho' Menezes

rim diameter: 28 kilometers (17.4 miles); age: 38 +- 4 million years   a heavily eroded complex structure. Eastward moving glaciers have drastically reduced the surface expression of this structure, removing most of the impact melt sheet and breccias and exposing the crater floor. Glacial erosion has also imparted an eastward elongation to the crater that is particularly evident in the shape of the lake that occupies the central 10 kilometers (6 miles) of the structure. Horseshoe Island, in the center of the lake, is part of the central uplift and contains shocked Precambrian crystalline target rocks. Just beyond the margins of the lake are vestiges of the impact melt sheet that contains evidence of meteoritic features in quartz, feldspar and diaplectic glasses.  Description from http://www.solarviews.com/eng/tercrate.htm

Pulau Redang is located in the South China Sea off the East Coast of Peninsular Malaysia within 5°44' - 5°50' North latitude and 102°59' - 103°5' East longitude. It lies about 45 km north-northeast of Kuala Terengganu, the state capital of Terengganu, and about 22 km off Tanjung Merang, the closest point on the mainland.
You will encounter many different species of fish as you snorkel or dive in the waters around the Pulau Redang Marine Park. Many of them can be found at relatively shallow depths since reefs thrive only in sunlight. Some of these you will recognize as food fishes you may have seen at seafood restaurants and on your dining table! Not surprising since reef fish form up to 25-30% of fishermen catch in local coastal communities. Many reef fishes are also 'resident' and home-ranging in that they do not wander from one reef to the next

Australia's Dog Barrier Fence stretches from the cliffs of the Nullabor Plain to the fertile farms of South-Eastern Queensland. At 5400km, it is the worlds's longest unbroken fence and is two and a half times the length of the Great Wall of China!

The fence was built in the early 1900's to keep wild dogs (dingos and cross-breed packs) out of South-Eastern Australia. As a general rule, sheep are on the eastern side and cattle, which are less vulnerable to dog attack, are in the west. While there are still some dingos and wild dogs on the eastern side, they are more easily controlled and the majority remain in the west.

The fence has maintenance tracks running on either side of it, and there are gates where it crosses major roads. Permission must be sought to travel on these maintenance tracks, and a 4WD with plenty of water and fuel is essential. Fence maintainance is the responsibility of the many local councils that it passes through. The fence is currently being electrified in stages.

While there is no doubt the fence protects millions of dollars worth of sheep, it has very much changed the ecology of central Australia and thousands of native animals die along the fence as they seek water and pasture during times of drought. While kangaroos can jump it, emus and other animals are not so lucky.

I have tried my best to mark the track using overlays of government maps. However the fence has never been officially surveyed and there are areas where the true fence path is in doubt and I have had to give it my best guess. There are several areas through central South Australia where low resolution has made it tricky to identify. Any corrections are welcome.

This is an example of a family Genealogy study. This is a complete list of all the locations of important people in the Chaffe, Chafe, Chaffee and Chaffey surname. I used many photos in the overlays to describe the area.

It is a family of explorers, politicians, farmers, fishermen, millionaires, entrepreneurs, inventors, actors, athletes, soldiers, clergymen, professors, doctors, engineers, benefactors, community leaders and even an astronaut.

The 'Chaffe' surname originally came from the present village of Chaffcombe, Somerset, England. The name Chaffcombe was listed in the Domesday Book commissioned by William the Conqueror in 1086. From that documented point the surname became tied to people from the village. The surname usage grew in size largely in the Somerset, Devon and Dorset areas. With the growth of the surname, both the written spelling and spoken word changed into a number of variations. In the 1600 and 1700's the surname became established in Canada and the United States where a number of these variations now predominate. The five most common variations that share the same ancestry are Chaffe/Chaffey (England), Chafe/Chaffey (Canada), Chaffee/Chaffey/Chafee (US) and Chaffey (Australia).

Please feel free to explore all the various links and discover more about this very interesting surname. Comments appreciated.

West Ham, London, City of birth of Lennox Lewis (Born 2 September 1965) world heavyweight Boxing champion.

Reign December 14, 1992-September 24, 1994 (WBC)
February 7, 1997-November 13, 1999 (WBC)
November 13, 1999-April 29, 2000 (IBF/IBO/WBA/WBC)

In early 2000 the World Boxing Association and Lewis were sued by representatives of John Ruiz claiming that they had reneged on an agreement by which Ruiz would have fought Lewis for the WBA title. A New Jersey court ruled in favor of Ruiz, and ordered Lewis to either have his next bout against Ruiz or relinquish the title. Lewis elected instead to fight contender Michael Grant, relinquishing his WBA title on the day of the match.

April 29, 2000-April 22, 2001 (IBF/IBO/WBC)
November 17, 2001-September 5, 2002 (IBF/IBO/WBC)

Lewis relinquished the IBF title upon receiving payment of $1 million (US) by promoter Don King, who wished to stage a bout between Chris Byrd and Evander Holyfield for the vacant title.(Pathetic!!)

September 5, 2002- February 6, 2004 (IBO/WBC)

Fight Record of Lennox Lewis



Quoted From Wikipedia :-

Lewis' boxing legacy is mixed. Despite having beaten the likes of Holyfield and Tyson, Lewis fought both when they were well past their primes, however they had both avoided him while in his prime. He was also highly criticized during his career for having a 'glass jaw', as evidenced by his shocking knockout losses by single punches to McCall and Rahman, both lightly-regarded, journeymen fighters. Furthermore, Lewis' deliberate style in the ring did not endear him to many in the boxing community, who expected the heavyweight champ to force the action in the ring. As a result, Lewis was often labeled as 'boring.'

column4: Auger Observatory on the Argentine Pampas
column5:
SD Station

Pierre Auger Observatory Surface Detector Station

This is one of some 1600 particle detectors scattered over a 3000km2 area for the Southern array of the Pierre Auger Observatory, in Mendoza province, Argentina. Another such array is planned for deployment in the Northern hemisphere, in Colorado, USA. With these detectors, the highest energy particles in the Universe are studied: when they strike the Earth's atmosphere, they create a cascade of billions of particles, which can be detected at the ground using water Cherenkov stations (tanks filled with water and equipped with sensitive light detectors). These particles are extremely rare, hence the need to deploy detectors over an enormous area to detect sufficient numbers of them. For more information on the Auger experiment, the water Cherenkov counters, and to see photographs of the actual detectors, see the official Pierre Auger collaboration web site.

The Carolina Parakeet (Conuropsis carolinensis), the only parakeet native to North America north of Mexico, was once abundant and ranged the wild southern swamps and forested river bottoms from Florida and the Gulf Coast as far north as New England and west into the Ohio and Wisconsin Valleys and toward the Midwestern Plains. A single subspecies lived only along the Gulf Coast. They ranged in flocks, fed on wild seeds of thistles, burweeds, beechnut, pecan, and conifers, and nested in holes in trees. As the land was settled the species was hunted for food and sport and trapped for the caged-bird industry, and with the planting of grain and orchards which the birds took advantage of, they were killed by the thousands. As suggested by the rapid disappearance of the last, small, but apparently healthy and reproducing flocks of these highly social birds, they succumbed to poultry disease. Under these circumstances the species rapidly decreased. From 1825 to 1832 John James Audubon noted the decrease of the parakeet and by 1880 few remained, although casual observers reported them until 1904. The caged-bird industry was evidently unsuccessful in breeding the species.___  Arundinaria gigantea is the only species of bamboo native to North America north of Mexico. Vast stands called “canebreaks” of Arundinaria once stretched throughout the southern and east from Florida to as far north as Ohio and growing as much as 30 feet tall. Early American botanist William Bartram described these thickets as having “no bounds but the skies.” On his walk from Indiana to Florida in 1868 John Muir saw banks of rough-hairgrass on the Savannah River, and “whole meadowfuls of bamboo.” Other explorers cursed them as impenetrable. And pioneer settlers recognized the lush growths for good soil, cleared the canebreaks, and planted crops. The demise of the American bamboo, along with much of the southern forests, was a major contributing factor in the extinction of the Carolina parakeet.___ View of intact forest along the Savannah River.
